| DL-31      | **CDE-Scoped Issue Tracking Creates Coverage Blind Spots.** The IMR procedure limits centralized issue tracking to **confirmed data quality issues related to CDEs/KDEs**, with other issues potentially tracked outside the central log. This creates a structural dependency on the completeness of the CDE inventory and excludes broader AML/OFAC data flows from consistent governance. | 504.3(c)(1)–(3), 504.3(c)(4)          | High        | Material data issues impacting transaction monitoring or filtering may not be centrally tracked, reducing visibility and weakening governance and certification support.                            | The IMR procedure states that only CDE/KDE-related issues are tracked in the centralized Branch Data Issue Log, while other issues may be handled separately, creating fragmented oversight.  |
| DL-32      | **Explicit Exclusion of Manual Data from Scope.** The IMR procedure excludes **manual data processes (e.g., spreadsheets, manual adjustments)** from in-scope data elements for issue tracking and governance.                                                                                                                                                                               | 504.3(c)(1)–(3), 504.3(c)(4)          | High        | Manual processes represent high-risk areas (e.g., payment screening workarounds, reconciliation adjustments, reporting overrides). Excluding them creates a blind spot in DFS 504 control coverage. | The IMR defines scope limitations that exclude manual data processes, which are often critical control points in AML and sanctions workflows.                                                 |
| DL-33      | **Issue Management Not Explicitly Linked to AML/OFAC Systems.** The IMR framework is designed as an enterprise data governance process and does not explicitly link issue management to key compliance systems such as **Prime (TM), FircoSoft (filtering), or RegTechOne (CRR)**.                                                                                                           | 504.3(a), 504.3(b), 504.3(c)(4)       | High        | AML/OFAC-specific data issues may not be prioritized appropriately, reducing the effectiveness of oversight over transaction monitoring and sanctions filtering data integrity.                     | The IMR procedure describes generic data issue management processes without referencing compliance systems or regulatory data flows.                                                          |
| DL-34      | **No DFS 504-Specific Severity and Escalation Triggers.** The IMR defines severity levels based on impact and data quality attributes but does not include **DFS 504-specific escalation triggers** such as missed transaction feeds, failed sanctions screening, or reconciliation breaks.                                                                                                  | 504.3(c)(4), 504.3(d)                 | High        | Critical AML/OFAC data integrity failures may not be escalated in a timely or consistent manner, increasing regulatory and operational risk.                                                        | Severity classification criteria are defined in general data quality terms without explicit linkage to AML/OFAC regulatory risk triggers.                                                     |
| DL-35      | **Issue Lifecycle Not Integrated with Change Management.** The IMR defines a lifecycle (identify, assess, remediate, validate, close) but does not explicitly require integration with formal change management processes for system or data fixes.                                                                                                                                          | 504.3(c)(4), 504.3(d)                 | Medium–High | Data issue remediation may bypass formal change controls, increasing the risk of introducing new defects or breaking existing data lineage.                                                         | The IMR lifecycle is defined independently of the Change Management / Testing Methodology, with no explicit requirement to route fixes through controlled change processes.                   |
